    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1892-03-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1892-03-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Wharton</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">von Holleben</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1892-03-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 24, 1892</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    Mr. von Mumm’s note of December 10, 1891, and of your own of the 23d instant, in
                    relation to the currency question at Samoa.</p>
                <p>It gives me pleasure to say that a telegram will be at once transmitted to Mr.
                    Sewell, the consul-general of the United States, Apia, instructing him to join
                    with his German and British colleagues, whenever they may receive similar
                    instructions, in representing to the Samoan Government that the Government of
                    the United States is of <pb facs="0641" n="635" xml:id="pg_635"/> opinion that
                    German coin should be admitted into Samoa as well as the coins of the United
                    States and Great Britain, the 20-mark gold piece to be taken as worth $4.76.</p>
                <p>Accept, sir, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William F. Wharton</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
